answers.body_markdown:
Your `servepath` handler apparently handles requests for `GET /api/:id`. When the browser receives the content of the `index.html` matching the `id` param, it probably finds references expressed as _relative_ paths like `&lt;script src=&quot;js/three.js&quot;&gt;`. To build the _fully qualified_ address to this resource, it uses the location of the current file. Which, in the case of the `index.html` you show, seems to be `http://localhost:3000/api/5d8b74be2af25086ab77fef7`.

A (quite) quick way of fixing this would be to:

- expose your projects statically (with `express.static` on the common folder to all your uploads which apparently ends with `/vr/uploads` now)
- then, instead of serving the `index.html` directly from `/api/:id`, use this route as a redirection to the proper static location

Something like that:
```js
// expose all uploads, under the URL http://localhost:3000/uploaded-projects/*
app.use(
  &#39;/uploaded-projects&#39;,
  express.static(path.join(__dirname, &#39;../../vr/uploads&#39;))
);
// handler to match a Mongo project ID with a public path under /uploaded-projects
app.get(`/api/:id`, (req, res) =&gt; {
  Upload.findById(req.params.id)
  .populate(&#39;Upload&#39;)
  .select(&#39;relPath&#39;)
  .exec((err, data) =&gt; {
    // ko: explicitly use an HTTP status otherwise it&#39;s 200
    if (err) return res.status(500).send(err);
    // ok: tell browser 302 + proper Location header
    res.redirect(`/uploaded-projects/${data.relPath}/index.html`);
  });
});
```
With maybe a bit more effort, you could alter your front-end so that, instead of using the ID in your list of projects, you use `relPath` (which you can provide to the front-end, since you already provide IDs and this `relPath` is inside the Mongo document) and a hard-coded path to the static tree (in my sketch, `/uploaded-projects`). This would allow the front-end to directly build the proper URL, hence avoiding to contact the server for a 302 and you could get rid of this `/api/:id` route.

